text: I'm sorry to say but it looks in the trailer more like Demetrius Shipp is doing an Impression of Tupac rather than being Tupac.  A mistake a lot of inexperienced actors make.  He already strongly resembles Pac so ge shouldn't have to try so hard. A better director would have been able to address this. Benny Boom has a lot of experience as a "video" director not a "film" director. The choice to choose these scenes in the trailer is also a director approval. Which is concerning.  As far as looks i do find myself distracted by how much fuller of a face and stockier he seems to be than pac.  He also looks shorter.  But its too hard to find an exact replica.  I am hoping his performance in the overall film will help me get past that. If you watched Straight outta Compton Jason Mitchell didn't look nor sound exactly like Eazy E but was able to capture the essence of him so you didn't pat as much attention to it.  Thats because he turned out to be a strong actor and F gary Gray is an experienced Director.  I hope the film turns out better than the trailer. I am cautiously optimistic but very worried it may be another Notorious, which would be a shame given how anticipated this film is.

text: Bottom line, is LT is fake ass cat. And Afeni had to battle LT and the studio after they sued her. The folks involved in this have shifty ass shit all over it. I know EDI and Noble both said they support this, but from what I see from these previews, is a portrayal of Tupac that is glorifying anger and material possessions. I see this Tupac as a man hungry for money and fame, that has random folks telling him he needs to know he was meant for greater. Get the fuck outta here with that. PAC was the one who KNEW his greatness, and KNEW that he needed to change the world. Pac's demons weren't something that he chased after, but were something that followed HIM.   I can't make my final thoughts until I see the movie, obviously. But even though I'm keeping an open mind, I can't shake the feeling that this shit is going to be a watered down, glorified soap opera of an angry black man fallen victim to "hood life" while chasing the white man's dream. Which is NOTHING close to Tupac and Tupac's story.

For instance, the fact that they are only showing his difficult times and "thug life" which isn't all he stood for but because they try to destroy the image of blacks, the easiest way to do so is by taking a little piece of something negative and elaborating on his faults. I can guarantee that this movie will not show you the poetic,smiling, great side of Tupac Amaru Shakur. I dont wanna go too deep into that black power, righteousness and the like but think about how when Black, Great leaders die, when the movie comes out about their lives they usually sugarcoat the good and expound heavily on the bad; destroying the image of not only the black person, but the people as a whole. text: I could say that about Biggie and 50 but Im commenting on Tupac.  Sorry to ruin your fantasy but Deathrow was a street gang. You have allowed your brain to separate one world of fame from the world gang violence.  People who are not in gangs dont ride down the street throwing up symbols with their fingers, yelling out, thuglife, outlaw immortals orbwhatever they are claiming this week. Toting illegal fire arms, brandishing them, intimidating people, riding on people and threatening to ride on people is gang banging.  Deathrow regularly jumped people, and put hits on people.  80% of the artists were known active gang members.  Tupac did what they did and gave his full support in their negative activities. Tupac and his fellow gang members banged on another known gang member and later on that evening his gang retaliated against tupac's gang.  Everybody in Compton knows what happened and who did what to who.  Its just some L.A. gang culture.  Tupac was in deep into it but he like everyone else signed to deathrow knew the risks.  Live by the gang culture you die by it.  He's still a great artist and the movie looks like it will be good.

What I'm actually worried about is will this film do justice to Pac's realness and genius soul? I might be asking for a lot considering it's Hollywood but a Tupac biopic really needs to show the world how incredibly intelligent and compassionate this guy was, not the IDGAF gangsta image he resented the media for trying to make him out to be, that portrayal would be shallow af for such a person, I mean just look at his own definition of 'thug life' trust me you'll be surprised. Hopefully this gives a real insight into Pac's amazing mind and heart. text: After this movie, Someone needs to make a movie about the East vs West Coast Event. I feel that people need to understand that the whole east coast west coast feud was a big media thing and to show what was really¬†going behind the scenes from all¬†important/ critical¬†vantage points.¬†I mean yes people can do more research on the internet but¬†in this modern age what better way then to put it in a movie to inflict interest of a situation¬†to an audience, influencing them to go and do more of their own research. It was a big event just like the Rodney king trials, O.J. Simpson trials, L.A. Riots, Police brutality back in the 80s-90s, etc.  I mean look at the show, "American Crime Story: The People v. O.J. Simpson", I was alive during that time yet I paid no attention to it but I heard about it and knew alittle about what it was, yet I never took interest in it until the show came out and when I started seeing how the show was a big deal on media, before I watched the show myself I did my research first and watched the whole trial on YouTube and watched the first movie that came out about O.J. Simpson and then I watched the show and saw the things that were happening behind the scenes that you didn't get to see in the news¬†unless you were actually there. Yes a few things were off in the show but the concept and idea and knowledge on the bit of American history was very educational to me and made me see things from a different light. That's why I feel they should make these movies for the younger generation.

text: Poems I wrote for Tupac...  TUPAC IS!! not was.. and ALWAYS will be!! the number one rapper in the world!! He inspires the masses in ways unknown Through his unique style, lyrically unscathed He's the king of rap & can't be overthrown Many have tried, but nobody can take his place  Their failed attempts are nothing but a disgrace The transparency of conspiracies to end his life All related to greed and unnecessary strife Has shown itself useless in silencing a born leader whose legacy only gets GREATER  His heart felt in every word  cut his enemies like a sword He gets the most love in the industry This caused jealousy and internal fury  TUPAC is a prophet bold & courageous, with a giving spirit, yes at times, outrageous His legend will continue to live on  and though we will all carry on He is who we will never forget A true POET  His name is Tupac Amaru Shakur They said he was gone but their words were premature His message and spirit are very much present A hero not for what he did, but for his intent Hear whats written in his music Truth in the form of a lyric A man of influence, also a non-conformist Faced with limited choices, became an opportunist A true soldier known world wide as multi-dimensional Offering and seeking love unconditional With a style anything but common His music remains an international phenomenon He had the courage to reveal so many truths, no matter how painful This is why his fans stay faithful Tupac's wish to spark a change in the world came true Just know that flame will continue It is he who at one time said, we aren't ready to see a black president That time came and went
